he success of these efforts. Surprisingly, he finds that presidents typically are not able to change public opinion; even great communicators usually fail to obtain the public's support for their high-priority initiatives. Focusing on presidents' personae, their messages, and the American public, he explains why presidents are often unable to move public opinion and suggests that their efforts to do so may be counterproductive. Edwards argues that shoring up previously existing support is the principal benefit of going public and that "staying private"-negotiating quietly with elites-may often be more conducive to a president's legislative success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommunication in politicsxUnited States. 0aCommunication in politicszUnited States. 0aPresidentsxPublic opinionxUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300133622.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles